\section{Type language}

We define a type environment |Gam| as follows:
\begin{syntaxdefs}
    \syntaxdef{|Gam|}
        \alt{|Gam[x +-> sig]|}
        \alt{|[]|}
\end{syntaxdefs}

Looking up the type of |x| in |Gam| is denoted as |Gam(x)|. This would if |x In dom(Gam)| return the type scheme associated with the right most occurrence of |x|.

We define our type language as follows:
\begin{syntaxdefs}
    \syntaxdef{|t|}
        \alt{|TyGeni|}
        \alt{|TyInt|}
        \alt{|TyFloat|}
        \alt{|TyString|}
        \alt{|TyBool|}
        \alt{|a|}
        \alt{|r|}
        \\
        \alt{|t -> t|}
        \\
        \alt{|[t]|}
%        \\
%        \alt{|(t1, ..., tn)| \quad |n >= 2|}
        \\
        \alt{|{l1 :: t1, ..., ln :: tn}| \quad |n >= 1|}
\end{syntaxdefs}

We define qualified types as follows:
\begin{syntaxdefs}
    \syntaxdef{|qt|}
        \alt{|preds => t|}
\end{syntaxdefs}

Type schemes are defined as:
\begin{syntaxdefs}
    \syntaxdef{|sig|}
        \alt{|forall i. sig|}
        \alt{|qt|}
\end{syntaxdefs}

\begin{syntaxdefs}
    \syntaxdef{|preds|}
        \alt{|r <: {x :: t}|}
        \alt{|C t|}
\end{syntaxdefs}